                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d349">
                <head>349. National Security Action Memorandum No. 251<note n="0" type="source"
                        xml:id="d349fn0">Source: Department of State, <gloss target="#t_SS1"
                            >S/S</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files: Lot 72 D 316,
                        NSAM 251. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-07-08">July 8, 1963</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Estimate of Greek Political Outlook</item>
                </list>
                <p>Before approving the proposed aide-memoire on U.S. aid to Greece arising out of
                    the <persName corresp="#p_PP1">Papaligouras</persName> visit, the President
                    would like the Department’s estimate of the Greek political outlook. In
                    particular he wonders what sort of alternative cabinets could emerge from the
                    current political crisis, and what the likely implications for U.S. interests of
                    each might be. If we face the prospect of prolonged jockeying and possible
                    renewed instability in Greek politics, is there anything the U.S. could or
                    should do about it?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">
                            <hi rend="strong">McGeorge Bundy</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
